abstract: In a new report, Democrats and Republicans denounced the “tough on crime” approach as unsparingly as they once promoted it.
snippet: In a new report, Democrats and Republicans denounced the “tough on crime” approach as unsparingly as they once promoted it.
lead_paragraph: One contributor to a new report on American criminal justice called the current system “an affront to our most fundamental values of freedom, equality and liberty,” then suggested sentencing fewer people to prison, sealing nonviolent criminal records and restoring voting rights for released offenders.

headline_main: Left and Right Agree on Criminal Justice: They Were Both Wrong Before
headline_print_headline: On This Issue, Both Sides  Concede They Were Wrong

abstract: Barring legal challenges, a new Alabama law would effectively outlaw abortions in the state. “This is a war on women,” Senator Kirsten Gillibrand said.
snippet: Barring legal challenges, a new Alabama law would effectively outlaw abortions in the state. “This is a war on women,” Senator Kirsten Gillibrand said.
lead_paragraph: For Senator Elizabeth Warren, the moment brought up memories of “back alley butchers” and “desperate women.” Senator Kamala Harris compared it to “a scene from ‘The Handmaid’s Tale.’” And Senator Kirsten Gillibrand warned about a “war on women,” calling for Americans to “fight like hell.”

abstract: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
snippet: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts on Tuesday broke from her Democratic rivals by declining to participate in a Fox News town hall, denouncing the cable news channel as “a hate-for-profit racket” that seeks to turns Americans against one another.

byline_original: By Michael M. Grynbaum and Matt Stevens

abstract: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
snippet: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
lead_paragraph: IOWA CITY — It may be nearly nine months until the first balloting of the 2020 primary, but candidates are already practically tripping over one another in Iowa.

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From the trade war with China to escalating tensions over the Mueller report, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: A co-founder is alarmed by Mark Zuckerberg’s power and wants to rein in the company.
snippet: A co-founder is alarmed by Mark Zuckerberg’s power and wants to rein in the company.
lead_paragraph: Chris Hughes, a co-founder of Facebook, pulls no punches in his essay for The Times Privacy Project, calling for a breakup of the company he helped launch from his Harvard dorm room 15 years ago.

headline_main: Chris Hughes’s Call to Break Up Facebook: 5 Takeaways

abstract: Mark Zuckerberg is a good guy. But the company I helped him build is a threat to our economy and democracy.
snippet: Mark Zuckerberg is a good guy. But the company I helped him build is a threat to our economy and democracy.
lead_paragraph: The last time I saw Mark Zuckerberg was in the summer of 2017, several months before the Cambridge Analytica scandal broke. We met at Facebook’s Menlo Park, Calif., office and drove to his house, in a quiet, leafy neighborhood. We spent an hour or two together while his toddler daughter cruised around. We talked politics mostly, a little about Facebook, a bit about our families. When the shadows grew long, I had to head out. I hugged his wife, Priscilla, and said goodbye to Mark.

abstract: Ms. Klobuchar, in a town hall event, called herself a “proven progressive,” while also appealing to Fox’s conservative viewers with her bipartisan record.
snippet: Ms. Klobuchar, in a town hall event, called herself a “proven progressive,” while also appealing to Fox’s conservative viewers with her bipartisan record.
lead_paragraph: Senator Amy Klobuchar of Minnesota defended her presidential candidacy as one that could appeal to both moderate and liberal voters, calling herself a “proven progressive” and casting her record as one of bipartisan accomplishment.
